[src:esp32/esp8266] In 2020, Espressif announced a new chip, ESP32-C3, which is pin-compatible with ESP8266.
[src:esp32/esp8266] It is based on a single core RISC-V 32-bit CPU with a clock speed of up to 160 MHz.
[src:esp32/esp8266] It includes 400 KiB of SRAM and 384 KiB ROM storage space built in.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] This document is intended to help you set up the software development environment for the hardware based on the ESP32 chip by Espressif.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] After that, a simple example will show you how to use ESP-IDF (Espressif IoT Development Framework) for menu configuration, then for building and flashing firmware onto an ESP32 board.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] This is documentation for stable version v6.0.2 of ESP-IDF.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Other ESP-IDF Versions are also available.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Powered by 40 nm technology, ESP32 offers excellent power efficiency, RF performance, security, and reliability, making it suitable for a wide range of application scenarios and power consumption requirements.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Espressif provides basic hardware and software resources to help application developers realize their ideas using the ESP32 series hardware.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] The software development framework by Espressif is intended for development of Internet-of-Things (IoT) applications with Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, power management and several other system features.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Currently, some of the development boards are using USB Type C connectors.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Be sure you have the correct cable to connect your board!
[src:esp32/get-started-index] If you have one of ESP32 official development boards listed below, you can click on the link to learn more about the hardware.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] To install ESP-IDF, build tools, and the toolchain, use the ESP-IDF Installation Manager (EIM) available for multiple operating systems.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Once you have the ESP-IDF installed, you can build your first project either using an IDE or from the command line.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] For instructions on how to set up and use these IDEs with ESP-IDF, please refer to their respective documentation linked above.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] If you have not yet installed ESP-IDF, please go to Installation and follow the instructions there to install all required software before proceeding.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] To uninstall ESP-IDF and related tools installed via EIM, you can use either the graphical user interface (GUI) or the command line interface (CLI).
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Launch the ESP-IDF Installation Manager.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] Under `Manage Installations`, click `Open Dashboard`.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] To remove a specific ESP-IDF version, click the `Remove` button under the version you want to remove.
[src:esp32/get-started-index] To remove all ESP-IDF versions, click `Purge All` button at the bottom of the page.
